Source citation rules for health content:

- Every health claim MUST have a cited scientific source with URL
- Never fabricate studies, journal names, or DOI numbers
- Preferred source hierarchy:
  1. Peer-reviewed journals (The Lancet, NEJM, JAMA, Nature Medicine, BMJ, Cell)
  2. Systematic reviews and meta-analyses (Cochrane Library)
  3. Official health organizations (WHO, CDC, ECDC, MOZ Ukraine)
  4. University research press releases (with link to original paper)
  5. Reputable health news (Medical News Today, Healthline — only as secondary)
- For each study cited, include: journal name, year, and URL/DOI when available
- For guides/lifehacks: cite at least 2 independent sources supporting each recommendation
- For research summaries: link to the original paper, not just a news article about it
- Distinguish between: RCT, observational study, meta-analysis, animal study, in-vitro
- Always note study limitations: sample size, population, duration
- Mark preliminary findings clearly: "попередні дані", "потрібні додаткові дослідження"
- NEVER present correlation as causation
- NEVER cite retracted papers